04032nam a22005055i 9780228003281DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280032817 a10.1515/97802280032812doi  a(DE-B1597)655543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aTR 7aPHO0050002bisacsh04a907.22231 aLangford, Martha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSuspended Conversations :bThe Afterlife of Memory in Photographic Albums Second Edition /cMartha Langford.  aSecond edition 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :bfull colour  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface: Hellohellohello -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface to the Second Edition -- tAcknowledgments to the Second Edition -- tIntroduction: Show and Tell -- tThe Idea of Album -- tThe Album as Collection -- tMemoirs and Travelogues -- tThe Idea of Family -- tOrality and Photography -- t“Photographs” 1916–1945 -- tConclusion: Remembering to Tell -- tA Note on the Photography Collection of the McCord Museum -- tThe Photographic Albums Illustrated in the Text -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Suspended Conversations Martha Langford shows how photographic albums tell intimate and revealing stories about individuals and families. Rather than isolate the individual photograph, treat albums as texts, or argue that photography has supplanted memory, she demonstrates that the photographic album must be taken as a whole and interpreted as a visual and verbal performance that extends oral consciousness.Exhibiting a collection of photographic travelogues, memoirs, thematic collections, and family sagas compiled between 1860 and 1960 and held by the McCord Museum of Canadian History, this second edition includes a revised and expanded preface along with new photographs of the Notman albums. Printed in colour throughout, the enhanced material draws out the distinct nuances and details of each album, giving them new life to tell their stories. Albums are treasured by families, collected as illustrations of the past by museums of social history, and examined by scholars for what they can reveal about attitudes and sensibilities, but when no one is left to tell the tale, the intrigue of the album becomes a puzzle, a suspended conversation. Langford argues that oral consciousness provides the missing key. Correlating photography and orality, she explains how albums were designed to work as performances and how we can unlock their mysteries.A fascinating glimpse of the preoccupations of previous centuries, Suspended Conversations brings photography into the great conversation of how we remember and how we send our stories into the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOral tradition. 0aPhotograph albumsxSocial aspects. 0aPhotographs in genealogy. 0aPhotography in historiography. 7aPhotography / Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228003281?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228003281423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228003281/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles